It may be well at this point to state the facts, so far as they are discoverable, as to the knowledge oi Manilius’ poemin classical times

It is usual to essert that the poem is not mentioned by any Roman writer. It is certain that Manilius is not included in the list ol poets mentioned by Ovid in the Tristia or that in the last book ol Epistles from Pontus, and that he is ignored by Quintilian. But it has not been observed that Ovid, although he has nowhere mentioned Manilius by name, seems to allude to two passages of his Vth book in these verses of the Trziteiz n 485, 486 Ecce canitsormas alens eiectusque pilarum, Hic arten nandipraeczbit, ille trochi. The description of the various ways . of swimming (Man. V. 420-431) is one of Manilius' happiest efforts ; the lines about ball-playing (165-171) are less detailed, but equally felicitous. Rudolf Merkel believed that the person whom Ovid attacked in his Ibis was Manilius, founding his view on the word Poeni which is added to his name in one MS. Though the uncertainty of this word, which as we have seen is spelt Boeni, Boeci, Boetii in other MSS, makes it of little value asan argument, there are at least two points in which the writer of the Ibis might seem to allude to Manilius. The first is the astrological reference Ib. 211-220 Natus es infelen, ita di uolnere, nec nlla Commoda nascenti stella lentim sui't. Non Venus illuxit, non illa Iuppiter horn. Lunaque non apto solque fuere loce. Nec satzi utiliter positos tibi praebuit ignes, Quen peperit magno lucida Maia Ioui.
